      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Great question! Besides the interest rate, a few other factors can influence how well your emergency fund performs:\n\n1. **Fees & Account Types**  \n   - **Account fees**: Some high‑yield savings accounts charge a monthly or annual fee. Make sure the fee is negligible compared to the interest you’ll earn.  \n   - **Deposit/withdrawal fees**: Check if there are any transaction fees for transferring money in or out.  \n   - **Minimum balance requirements**: Some accounts require a minimum deposit to avoid a fee or to qualify for the highest rate.  \n\n2. **Liquidity & Accessibility**  \n   - How quickly can you withdraw or transfer funds? High‑yield savings accounts usually offer 24/7 online access, but check the bank’s withdrawal terms.  \n\n3. **Interest Compounding**  \n   - Does the account compound interest daily, monthly, or annually? More frequent compounding can boost your earnings slightly.  \n\n4. **One‑Place vs. Multiple Places**  \n   - **All in one**: Simpler to manage, fewer accounts to track, and you can benefit from a single interest rate.  \n   - **Split up**: If you split the $15,00",
